%TAG !u! tag:unity3d.com,2011:
--- !u!114 &11400000
MonoBehaviour:
  m_ObjectHideFlags: 0
  m_CorrespondingSourceObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabInstance: {fileID: 0}
  m_PrefabAsset: {fileID: 0}
  m_GameObject: {fileID: 0}
  m_Enabled: 1
  m_EditorHideFlags: 0
  m_Script: {fileID: 11500000, guid: d1d62931ab01cd14b84145ae3bdd017f, type: 3}
  m_Name: Chapter 2
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  chapter: 2
  levelTerms:
  - level: 6
    terms:
    - term: Rectilinear Motion
      symbol: 
      type: 0
      definition: It is defined as motion along a straight line.
      explanation: "By definition, it means that everything behaves in a linear manner,
        so the objects and scenarios involved are only moving along one (1) of the
        three (3) known axes that we use (x, y, z). An example would be a car driving
        along the straight highway, without any other cars interfering its \r\nmovement."
    - term: Distance
      symbol: m
      type: 2
      definition: It is the total measured length between two (2) given points.
      explanation: "Simply put, if we use a simple racetrack, it \r\nis measured
        from Start to the Finish line."
    - term: Displacement
      symbol: x
      type: 2
      definition: "The measured mean distance covered \r\nbetween two (2) specified
        points. "
      explanation: Displacement is a certain distance at any given two (2) points.
        So, going back to the track, the displacement could be from Start to the
        middle, middle to the Finish line, or it could also be the average distance
        between the Start and the Finish line; used interchangeably with distance.
    - term: Time
      symbol: s
      type: 2
      definition: "The progression of events occurring between \r\ninstances."
      explanation: It is something we need to prove that there is a progression between
        events, such as from walking to running, jogging from point A to B, and so
        on.
    - term: Speed
      symbol: v
      type: 3
      definition: The scalar quantity defined as the total distance covered per unit
        time.
      explanation: 'Simply put, if there is motion, there is speed. Speed does not,
        and cannot, have a negative value. Sometimes, it is interchanged with velocity.


        Formula:

        v
        = | d / t |


        v = speed

        d = distance

        t = time'
    - term: Velocity
      symbol: "v\u02C9"
      type: 3
      definition: "The measured speed measured between two \r\n(2) specified points."
      explanation: "It is the measured speed in a certain distance at any given instance
        in time. However, unlike speed, velocity is a vector quantity and requires
        direction. Negative velocity values indicate that the objects are moving
        in the opposite direction.\n\nFormula:\nv\u02C9 = x / t\n\nv\u02C9 = velocity\nx
        = displacement\nt = time"
    - term: Acceleration
      symbol: a
      type: 3
      definition: The change in velocity per unit time.
      explanation: "It shows how fast the object moves in order to reach that certain
        amount of velocity within a certain amount of time. Negative acceleration
        values indicate that the objects are slowing down.\n\nFormula:\na = v\u02C9\u200B
        / t\n\na = acceleration\nv\u02C9 = velocity\nt = time"
  - level: 7
    terms:
    - term: Two-Dimensional Motion
      symbol: "V<sub>R</sub>\xB2"
      type: 2
      definition: Projected within Cartesian plane with x and y.
      explanation: "We can present vectors within a Cartesian plane. As previously
        discussed as well, rectilinear motion is, simply put, motion along a straight
        line. So, projecting it within a Cartesian plane, it will only move either
        along the x-axis or the y-axis.\n\nFormula:\nV<sub>R</sub>\xB2 = V<sub>x</sub>\xB2
        + V<sub>y</sub>\xB2\n\nV<sub>R</sub>\xB2 = resultant velocity\r\nV<sub>x</sub>\xB2
        = x velocity\r\nV<sub>y</sub>\xB2 = y velocity"
    - term: Resultant
      symbol: 
      type: 0
      definition: It is the third arrow alongside x and y axes.
      explanation: "It represents the motion in both dimensions. \r\nSimply put,
        it simplifies the direction taken by the object throughout its movement."
  - level: 9
    terms:
    - term: Relative Motion
      symbol: 
      type: 2
      definition: It is a movement that is observed from another point of view.
      explanation: "This motion requires three (3) reference frames the static reference
        (always referred to as A), the intermediate reference (referred to as B),
        and the moving reference (referred to as C). Since there is a common ground
        for both velocities, the formula is simply a linear vector equation, though
        it may change to suit the scenario.\n\nFormula:\nV<sub>AC</sub>\xB2 = V<sub>AB</sub>\xB2
        + V<sub>BC</sub>\xB2\n\nV<sub>AB</sub>\xB2 = train speed from ground\nV<sub>BC</sub>\xB2
        = human walking speed in train\nV<sub>AC</sub>\xB2 = (resultant) human speed
        from ground\n\n"
